<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FIESTAS SCHEDULED AROUND THE BAY FOR CINCO
DE MAYO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     And thirst-quenching jugos and fresh salsa, made from ripe tomatoes,
cilantro, onions and spices.;    These are just a few of the sights, sounds
and tastes you'll find at the annual Cinco de Mayo fiestas taking place this
weekend in San Jose and around the Bay Area.;    Cinco de Mayo celebrates the
courageous Mexican patriots who fought against well-armed French invaders on
the 5th of May in 1862.;    Led by General Ignacio Zaragoza, the patriots of
Puebla defended their homeland with barely more than sticks and rocks. Their
bravery in the face of hopeless odds won the battle -- a triumph that has
gained emotional and historical significance through time.;    Today, the
festival celebrates Mexican-Americans' ethnic pride and heritage, as well as
the glory at Puebla. It is also an opportunity for non-Hispanics to take
delight in Mexican culture.;    Cinco de Mayo festivities range from a
downtown parade to art exhibits, lectures, arts and crafts displays and live
entertainment.; San Jose; (box) Cinco de Mayo Art Exhibit.; "The Historical,
Traditional and Cultural Puebla de Zaragoza," photographs by Mary J. Andrade,
through June 1. 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Mondays through Saturdays; noon to 5 p.m.
Sundays. Machu Picchu, El Paseo Court, 42 S. First St., San Jose. (408)
280-1860.;    The display is also on exhibit through June 5 at the East
Carnegie Library, 1102 E. Santa Clara St., San Jose. (408) 998-2069.;    (box)
Festival del Sol;    Today and Saturday:;    Food, non-alcoholic drinks and
non-stop entertainment will be offered from 11 a.m. to 8 p.m. today and
Saturday at Plaza Park in downtown San Jose.;    The event will feature Little
Joe and the Familia, Dr. Loco and his Rockin' Jalapeno Band and Mexican
artists.;    Opening ceremonies will be at noon Friday, and a children's
procession with cartoon characters, clowns and magicians will begin at 11 a.m.
Saturday.;    Admission is free. For information, call (408) 293-6484.;   
(box) Cinco de Mayo Fiesta for children.;    Saturday:;    South-of-the-border
treats, pinatas, music and carnival games will entertain children from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. at the Solari Community Center, 3590 Cas Drive, San Jose. (408)
224-0415.;    (box) Downtown Cinco de Mayo Celebration.;    Sunday:;   
Fiesta: 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. With about 150 booths selling food, arts and crafts.
Almaden Boulevard, downtown San Jose. Free. Sponsored by the American GI Forum
of San Jose (408) 923-1646.;    Parade: 10 a.m. Led by the grand marshal, Joe
Kapp, it will start at Ninth and E. Santa Clara streets, head south on Market
Street and disband at San Carlos Street.;    The parade features actor Ernie
Reyes Jr. (a native of San Jose now starring in "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles
II"), Gisette Chamorro (Reina de las Fiestas Patrias), Diana Marie Estrada
(Miss San Jose GI Forum) and Monica Gomez (Miss American GI Forum), as well as
the West Coast Movement, a self-motivation/drug-abuse prevention program.;   
Local high school marching bands will compete for the $500 Best Band first
prize in the parade, along with junior high schools competing for the $200
prize.;    Mexican arts and crafts: "Centro de Nuestra Cultura" ("Center of
Our Culture") is in the old Convention Center at Park Avenue and Market Street
from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Sunday.;    Free entertainment: Three stages feature
live music, beginning at 10 a.m. Sunday. The groups include: 19th Street Band,
Valentino, Us Four, NVS, Cana Dulce, Nite-liters, Los Duques, Bernie Fuentes,
Super Amor, Jaguar, Pedro Landa, and Angeles Ocha.;    "Centro de Nuestra
Cultura": The old Convention Center at Park Avenue and Market Street features
entertainment from 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m., Sunday .;    Performing will be: El
Grito de La Cultura directed by Elena Robles, Mariachi Azteca de Pato Diaz,
Los Danzantes de San Jose directed by Brian Gaeta, tae kwon do demonstration
by Ernie Reyes Jr., Grupo Tezcatlipoca Aztec dancers directed by David Vargas,
Los Mestizos dancers directed by Teresa Rodriguez, and Danzantes de Aztlan
directed by Margaret Diaz.;    Stanford University; (box) Through May 31:;   
Jose Antonio Burciaga art exhibit. Second floor Tressider Lounge.;    (box)
Today:;    Dr. Loco and his Rockin' Jalapeno Band. Performs a blend of rock,
blues, salsa, cumbia and Norteno from 9 p.m. to 2 a.m. at Burnham Pavilion.
Sponsored by El Centro Chicano and the Centennial Operating Committee.;    The
Sixth Annual Ernesto Galarza Commemorative Lecture by Polly Baca. Executive
director, Colorado Institute for Hispanic Education and Economic Development,
and a former state senator. 4 to 6 p.m. History Corner, Room 2. Presented by
the Stanford Center for Chicano Research.;    (box) Saturday:;    Stanford
Chicano Alumni Conference. 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Littlefield Center, Room 107,
Graduate School of Business. Registration 9 to 10 a.m. Following registration
is a student/alumni reception at Casa Zapata. Preregistration $20; on-site
registration $5 for students and $25 for non-students.;    Teatro Xicano de
Stanford Performance. 7 p.m. Casa Zapata. Improvisational theater by
undergraduate and graduate students. Free admission.;    Cinco de Mayo
Celebration. 9 p.m. to 2 a.m. Casa Zapata, sponsored by the Chicano/Latino
preprofessional groups.;    (box) Sunday:;    Cinco de Mayo Fiesta. 1 p.m.
Presented by Casa Zapata, features Ballet Folklorico de Stanford, mariachi
music, and dinner. Call El Centro Chicano at Stanford (415) 723-2089.;   
Cinco de Mayo Bilingual Mass. 4:30 p.m. Kresge Auditorium.;    (box) Monday:; 
  Testimony, Narrative Truth, and The Latin American Postmodernity: On I.
Rigoberta Menchu. Noon. Department of Spanish and Portuguese lounge, Wilbur
Modules B-5. Lecture by John Beveley, author and professor.;    (box)
Tuesday:;    Re-envisioning Chicano Studies. 3 to 5:30 p.m, El Centro Chicano.
Panel discussion presented by the Chicano Fellows Program/Undergraduate
Studies on Mexican Society and Culture.;    A Night with Enrigue Ramirez and
his Trio. 7 to 9 p.m. Coffee House. Nueva Cancion. Presented by the Coffee
House and MECHA.;    (box) Friday, May 10:;    El Grupo Cultural Zero presents
"La Mitad del Cielo" ("Half of The Sky") at 7 p.m. in Kresge Auditorium. The
performance is in Spanish, but the story about a traveling vendor is
self-explanatory. English program notes are available. Tickets are $7 for
adults and $4 for seniors/students/children. Call (415) 723-4317.;    (box)
Friday, May 24, and Saturday, May 25:;    El Concierto de la Primavera. 8 p.m.
Ballet Folklorico de Stanford. Dinkelspiel Auditorium.;    (box) Friday, May
31:;    Quincentennial Poetry Reading. Presented by Casa Zapata. Time and
place to be announced. Call (415) 723-2089.;    Watsonville; (box) Cinco De
Mayo Celebration. Sponsored by the Fiestas Patrias Committee. Live
entertainment. Sunday, noon to 6 p.m., Plaza Central, corner of Main and East
Beach streets, downtown Watsonville. Free. (408) 724-9005 or (408) 724-2997.; 
  San Francisco; (box) Two-day festival sponsored by the Mission Economic
Cultural Association (415) 826-1401.;    (box) Saturday.; Festival at Civic
Center Plaza. Noon-7 p.m. Food, arts and crafts booths. Across from City Hall
at Larkin, McAlister and Polk streets. Carnival rides for kids in an enclosed
area. Festival admission price is $3; youths under 14 are free.;    The
Healthy High Five Races. Beginning at 8 a.m., there will be five different
races: a run, a power walk, roller-skating or roller-blading, skateboarding
and costume team run competition. At Mission Delores Park (near 22nd and
Delores streets), concluding at the Healthy High Five Pavilion at the festival
site at Civic Center Plaza (across from the east side of City Hall at Larkin,
McAlister and Polk streets). Admission in advance is $10; day of event is
$15.;    Healthy High Pavilion. 30 booths for health-care organizations,
providing information, demonstrations, medical testing (including confidential
AIDS testing and glaucoma testing) and health food-product sampling. Bilingual
services.;    Festival Mainstage Entertainment: A.S.P. (bilingual rappers),
guitarist Ray Obiedo ("Iguana" album on Windham Hill) performs Latin jazz
fusion, Orestes Vilato (timbales player with Santana) with Los Kimbos,
Mariachi Nacional de Mexico.;    Festival Folkloric Entertainment: Ballet
Folklorica de Stanford, Ballet Folkloric Nayarita.;    (box) Sunday.; Parade.
11 a.m. Led by singer Linda Rondstadt as the grand marshal on her own float
with mariachis.;    The parade of floats, televised live on KOFY-TV (Ch. 20)
and aired again later in the evening, begins at 24th and Bryant streets at 11
a.m., moves on 24th and Mission to Civic Center in front of City Hall.;   
Festival at Civic Center Plaza. Noon to 7 p.m. Food, arts and crafts booths.
Across from City Hall at Larkin, McAlister and Polk streets. Carnival rides
for kids in an enclosed area. Festival admission price is $3; children under
14 admitted free.;    Festival Mainstage Entertainment. MC Phame (bilingual
rappers), Los Pregoneros del Puerto, Dr. Loco and his Rockin' Jalapeno Band,
Bandido, Los Lobos.;    Festival Folkloric Entertainment. South San Francisco
Children's Ballet Folkloric, Grupo Azatlan, Trio Tamunal, Teokalli Aztec
Dancers, Mariachi Nacional de Mexico, Xochipilli.;    Berkeley; (box) Sunday:;
Cinco de Mayo Celebration with Los Pregoneros del Puerto. The music of
Veracruz with Jose Gutierrez, Gonzalo Mata, Oliverio Reyes, Valente Reyes. La
Pena Cultural Center, 3105 Shattuck Ave., Berkeley. (415) 849-2568.  </TEXT>
